Goal¶

To build a probabilistic model that can accurately predict whether a person is susceptible to heart disease, given some of his/her clinical parameters, age and gender. The dataset to be used for training our model is https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fedesoriano/heart-failure-prediction.

Modelling¶

First we explore a simple probabilistic binary classification model on our dataset $D$ consisting of $N$ observations of the targets $y_{n} \in$ {0, 1} which depend on their corresponding explanatory variables $x_n$

                         $D = ${$\textbf{x}_n, y_n$}$_{n=1}^N$

Generative Process¶

  1. Draw coefficients $\beta \sim \mathcal{N}(\textbf{0}, \lambda I)$
  2. Draw coefficients $\alpha \sim \mathcal{N}(\textbf{0}, \tau I)$
  3. For every data point n = {1,...,N}
    a. Draw class $y_n \sim Bernoulli(Softmax(\alpha + \beta^T \textbf{x}_n))$

We convert the categorical variables into one-hot encoded columns. We also feature scale the numerical features in the dataset and concatenate it with the one-hot encoded variables, to complete the training set. We did a 75-25% train-test split.

In [352]:
def classification_model(X, N_categories, obs=None):
    N_features = X.shape[1]
    alpha = pyro.sample("alpha", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(1, N_categories), \
                                             0.5*torch.ones(1, N_categories)).to_event())
    beta = pyro.sample("beta", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_features, N_categories), \
                                           0.5*torch.ones(N_features, N_categories)).to_event())
    
    with pyro.plate("data", X.shape[0]):
        y = pyro.sample("y", dist.Categorical(logits=alpha.double() + X.matmul(beta.double())), obs=obs)
    
    return y

Hierarchical Model by Gender¶

In the exploratory data analysis, we discovered that men are more susceptible to heart disease than women, according to our data. A simple binary classification model assumes that all individuals have identical biases and give same importance to all features, and a single set of parameters is used for all the observations. We can instead explore a hierarchical model, which divides the individuals into two groups based on gender. The data from each group gets its own set of parameters and a shared global prior ties together the parameters for each group.

Part 1 - Priors on the bias¶

We can design a hierarchical model in many ways. We first set a hierarchical prior on the intercepts (biases) and defined our model according to the following generative process.

Generative Process¶

  1. Draw global mean parameter $\mu_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)$
  2. Draw global variance parameter $\sigma_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{HalfCauchy}(0, 10)$
  3. Draw coefficients $\boldsymbol\beta$ $\sim \mathcal{N}(\textbf{0}, 10\mathbf{I})$
  4. For each group(gender) g $\in$ {M, F}
    a. Draw coefficients $\alpha^{g} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\alpha})$
  5. For each data point n = {1, ..., N}
    a. Draw class $y_n \sim Bernoulli(Softmax( \textbf{x}_n, \alpha^{g}, \boldsymbol\beta))$

def hierarchical_gender_model_0(X, N_categories, N_genders, gender_ind, obs=None):
    N_features = X.shape[1]
    alpha_mu = pyro.sample("alpha_mu", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_categories), \
                                                   10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    alpha_sigma  = pyro.sample("alpha_sigma",  dist.HalfCauchy(10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    beta  = pyro.sample("beta", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_features, N_categories), \
                                            10.*torch.ones(N_features, N_categories)).to_event())
    
    with pyro.plate("genders", N_genders):
        alpha = pyro.sample("alpha", dist.Normal(alpha_mu, alpha_sigma).to_event(1))
    with pyro.plate("data", X.shape[0]):
        logits = alpha[gender_ind].double() + X.matmul(beta.double())
        y = pyro.sample("y", dist.Categorical(logits=logits), obs=obs)
        
    return y

Part 2 - Priors on the bias and weights¶

We can also add a global prior to the $\beta$ regressive coefficients, so that they take up different sets of values depending on the age group. Now with additional complexity, we might be increasing the chance of overfitting, but let's see what happens.

Generative Process¶

  1. Draw global mean parameter for bias $\mu_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)$
  2. Draw global variance parameter for bias $\sigma_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{HalfCauchy}(0, 10)$
  3. Draw global mean parameter for weights $\mu_{\beta} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)$
  4. Draw global variance parameter for weights $\sigma_{\beta} \sim \mathcal{HalfCauchy}(0, 10)$
  5. For each group(gender) g $\in$ {M, F}
    a. Draw coefficients $\alpha^{g} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\alpha})$
    b. Draw coefficients $\boldsymbol \beta^{g} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\beta}, \sigma_{\beta})$
  6. For each data point n = {1, ..., N}
    a. Draw class $y_n \sim Bernoulli(Softmax( \textbf{x}_n, \alpha^{g}, \boldsymbol\beta^{g}))$
In [383]:
def hierarchical_gender_model(X, N_categories, N_genders, gender_ind, obs=None):
    N_features = X.shape[1]
    alpha_mu = pyro.sample("alpha_mu", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_categories), \
                                                   10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    alpha_sigma  = pyro.sample("alpha_sigma",  dist.HalfCauchy(10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    beta_mu = pyro.sample("beta_mu", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_features, N_categories), \
                                                 10.*torch.ones(N_features, N_categories)).to_event())
    beta_sigma  = pyro.sample("beta_sigma",  dist.HalfCauchy(10.*torch.ones(N_features, N_categories)).to_event())
    with pyro.plate("genders", N_genders):
        alpha = pyro.sample("alpha", dist.Normal(alpha_mu, alpha_sigma).to_event(1))
        beta = pyro.sample("beta", dist.Normal(beta_mu, beta_sigma).to_event(2))
    with pyro.plate("data", X.shape[0]):
        logits = alpha[gender_ind].double() \
                + torch.stack([X[i].matmul(beta[gender_ind][i].double()) for i in range(X.shape[0])])
        y = pyro.sample("y", dist.Categorical(logits=logits), obs=obs)
        
    return y

Hierarchical Model by Age¶

Another way we could explore grouping of individuals is via age of the individuals. If the susceptibility towards heart disease is significantly different between age groups, then we could assign distinct biases to those groups while designing the model. First we could need to explore if there is indeed a difference in susceptibility.

We decided to split the observations into 3 groups based on the distribution of age in the data.
a. Individuals with age < $\mu - 0.5\sigma$ (denoted by 0)
b. Individuals with $\mu - 0.5\sigma$ $\le$ age $\le$ $\mu + 0.5\sigma$ (denoted by 1)
c. Individuals with age > $\mu + 0.5\sigma$ (denoted by 2)

In [427]:
def age_to_level(age):
    if age <= age_mean+0.5*age_std and age >= age_mean-0.5*age_std:
        return 1
    elif age < age_mean-0.5*age_std:
        return 0
    elif age > age_mean+0.5*age_std:
        return 2

As expected, young people are less likely to get heart disease and the susceptibility is to heart disease is more in higher age groups. We can commence with our hierarchical model using these 3 age groups. We just define priors on the biases (intercepts) and not on the $\beta$ coefficients.

Generative Process¶

  1. Draw global mean parameter $\mu_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)$
  2. Draw global variance parameter $\sigma_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{HalfCauchy}(0, 10)$
  3. Draw coefficients $\boldsymbol\beta$ $\sim \mathcal{N}(\textbf{0}, 10\mathbf{I})$
  4. For each group(age level) a $\in$ {0, 1, 2}
    a. Draw coefficients $\alpha^{a} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\alpha})$
  5. For each data point n = {1, ..., N}
    a. Draw class $y_n \sim Bernoulli(Softmax( \textbf{x}_n, \alpha^{a}, \boldsymbol\beta))$

def hierarchical_age_model(X, N_categories, N_agegroups, age_ind, obs=None):
    N_features = X.shape[1]
    alpha_mu = pyro.sample("alpha_mu", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_categories), 10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    alpha_sigma  = pyro.sample("alpha_sigma",  dist.HalfCauchy(10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    beta  = pyro.sample("beta", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_features, N_categories), 10.*torch.ones(N_features, N_categories)).to_event())
    
    with pyro.plate("age groups", N_agegroups):
        alpha = pyro.sample("alpha", dist.Normal(alpha_mu, alpha_sigma).to_event(1))
    with pyro.plate("data", X.shape[0]):
        logits = alpha[age_ind].double() + X.matmul(beta.double())
        y = pyro.sample("y", dist.Categorical(logits=logits), obs=obs)
        
    return y

Hierarchical Model by Age and Gender¶

We can combine the two hierarchical models above to design a hierarchy based on two levels - gender and age. We do this by assigning a bias $\gamma$ seperately encoding the bias for age groups, along with $\alpha$ encoding the bias for different genders. We state the global priors that tie together the parameters for each level seperately for gender and age groups.

Generative Process¶

  1. Draw global mean parameter for gender bias $\mu_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)$
  2. Draw global variance parameter for gender bias $\sigma_{\alpha} \sim \mathcal{HalfCauchy}(0, 10)$
  3. Draw global mean parameter for age bias $\mu_{\gamma} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 10)$
  4. Draw global variance parameter for age bias $\sigma_{\gamma} \sim \mathcal{HalfCauchy}(0, 10)$
  5. Draw coefficients $\boldsymbol\beta$ $\sim \mathcal{N}(\textbf{0}, 10\mathbf{I})$
  6. For each group(gender) g $\in$ {M, F}
    a. Draw coefficients $\alpha^{g} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\alpha})$
  7. For each group(age level) a $\in$ {0, 1, 2}
    a. Draw coefficients $\gamma^{a} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\gamma}, \sigma_{\gamma})$
  8. For each data point n = {1, ..., N}
    a. Draw class $y_n \sim Bernoulli(Softmax( \textbf{x}_n, \alpha^{g}, \gamma^{a}, \boldsymbol\beta))$

def hierarchical_gender_age_model(X, N_categories, N_genders, N_agegroups, age_ind, gender_ind, obs=None):
    N_features = X.shape[1]
    alpha_mu = pyro.sample("alpha_mu", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_categories), \
                                                   10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    alpha_sigma  = pyro.sample("alpha_sigma",  dist.HalfCauchy(10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    beta  = pyro.sample("beta", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_features, N_categories), \
                                            10.*torch.ones(N_features, N_categories)).to_event())
    with pyro.plate("genders", N_genders):
        alpha = pyro.sample("alpha", dist.Normal(alpha_mu, alpha_sigma).to_event(1))
        
    gamma_mu = pyro.sample("gamma_mu", dist.Normal(torch.zeros(N_categories), \
                                                   10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    gamma_sigma  = pyro.sample("gamma_sigma",  dist.HalfCauchy(10.*torch.ones(N_categories)).to_event())
    
    with pyro.plate("age levels", N_agegroups):
        gamma = pyro.sample("gamma", dist.Normal(gamma_mu, gamma_sigma).to_event(1))
        
    with pyro.plate("data", X.shape[0]):
        logits = gamma[age_ind].double() + alpha[gender_ind].double() + X.matmul(beta.double())
        y = pyro.sample("y", dist.Categorical(logits=logits), obs=obs)
        
    return y

Let's explore gaussian process classification now, and see if there's an improvement in the accuracy.

Classification using Gaussian Processes¶

$\textbf{Gaussian Processes}$ have been used in supervised, unsupervised, and even reinforcement learning problems and are described by an elegant mathematical theory They are also very attractive conceptually, since they offer an intuitive way to define priors over functions. And finally, since Gaussian Processes are formulated in a Bayesian setting, they come equipped with a powerful notion of uncertainty. Pyro offers some support for Gaussian Processesin the pyro.contrib.gp module. Therefore, $\textbf{Gaussian Processes Classifier (GPCs)}$ Gaussian Process Classifier models has been implemented to improve the model performance.

The model were interested in is defined by $\textbf{f}$ ~ $\textit{GP}$($\textbf{0}$,$K_f$($\textit(x,x')$) \& $\textbf{y = f(x) }$+ $\epsilon$

Here $\textit(x,x')$ $\epsilon$ $\textit(X)$ are points in the input space and $\textit(y)$ $\epsilon$ $\textit(Y)$ f is a point in the output space. f is a draw from the GP prior specified by the kernel $K_f$ and represents a function from to . Finally, $\epsilon$ represents Gaussian observation noise.

Conclusion¶

Multiple training attempts and models later, we find that the test set accuracy for the bayesian logistic regression models and the hierarchical logistic regression models generally hover around 85-87% and do not improve significantly even after adding more levels, and training for longer. It's likely that the distinction between groups in the hierarchical models are not significant enough over large amount of data, to be an improvement over the plain bayesian logistic regression model. Placing identical biases and weights to all observations works equally well as not doing so (hierarchies).

However, a significant improvement is seen when we trained a Gaussian Process Classifier on the same dataset for heart disease prediction. The test set accuracy is 92.17%. We found this to be the best bayesian model for our task.
